---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Nav from "@/components/Nav.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";

const navLinks = [
  { href: "/", label: "Phidea" },
  { href: "/#archive", label: "Topics" },
  { href: "/#subscribe", label: "Subscribe" },
];
const navCta = { href: "#subscribe", label: "Subscribe →" };
---

<Layout variant="ai-visibility">
  <Nav variant="ai-visibility" links={navLinks} cta={navCta} />

  <article class="article">
    <header class="article-head">
      <div class="wrap wrap-article">
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>Topic 01 · Distribution</span>
          <span>April 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>When a carrier isn't cited by ChatGPT.</h1>
        <p class="standfirst">
          The carriers ranked highest on Google are often not the ones ChatGPT mentions. The gap is not a mistake. It is a different system.
        </p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="article-body">
      <div class="wrap wrap-article">
        <p>
          Something has changed in how people find their insurance. They used to begin on Google. Now, more and more, they open ChatGPT or Claude or Gemini or Perplexity, and they ask. In every market we have looked at, "Am I covered for X?" is typed into an AI assistant more often than into a comparison site.
        </p>

        <p>
          This matters more than most carriers realise. The answer the assistant gives is not a ranked list of links. It is a sentence. A sentence that may name your carrier, may name a competitor, or may name no one at all. The sentence is composed by the model from whatever it has read.
        </p>

        <p>
          Consider what the model has read. It has trained, some months ago, on a slice of the internet. It has access, when you ask, to real-time web search. And it has an internal sense of which brands are worth mentioning, built from thousands of articles that discuss insurance in different ways.
        </p>

        <p>
          None of this corresponds to your search engine ranking. A carrier that dominates Google may barely appear on Perplexity. This is not a bug. It is simply a different system, running on different signals.
        </p>

        <p>
          In the probes we have run across several markets, the pattern is consistent. The carriers cited most often by the assistants are not the ones ranked highest on Google. They are the ones most frequently mentioned on sites like NerdWallet, Insurance Business, and the comparison media. Earned media has always been valuable. In an AI-assistant world it is, for the first time, measurable as a form of distribution.
        </p>

        <p>
          So what can a carrier do?
        </p>

        <p>
          First, make sure the assistants can see you. ChatGPT, Claude, Perplexity, and Google all operate crawlers that respect <code>robots.txt</code>. Many carriers still block them — sometimes by accident, after an SEO migration no one has looked at in years. If the crawler cannot read your site, the model cannot cite you.
        </p>

        <p>
          Second, write your product pages in the shape an AI finds easiest to quote. A question-and-answer structure works better than a prose description. This is not about keywords. It is about the shape of the text.
        </p>

        <p>
          Third, remember that each assistant has its own personality. Claude refuses to quote specific prices. ChatGPT and Gemini will. Perplexity relies heavily on retrieval, and will cite whichever carrier has the clearest structured data on the open web. Optimising for one assistant does not optimise for all four.
        </p>

        <p>
          Fourth, measure what the models are saying about you today. Run a handful of real buyer queries on each assistant, and note who is cited. Compare the number with your actual market share. The gap tells you how much work there is to do.
        </p>

        <p>
          Finally, write your policy text in language that can survive being quoted back to a customer. When someone asks, "Am I covered for flooding while I am abroad?" the model does not copy your policy. It composes. If the original text is ambiguous, the composition will be confident — and often wrong. The cure is not to hide your text. It is to write it more clearly.
        </p>

        <p>
          This is the first in a small weekly series. Each issue looks at one corner of how AI is changing the insurance business, and, when I can, what a sensible carrier is doing about it. If you find it useful, the subscribe box is below.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="subscribe" class="subscribe-strip">
      <div class="wrap wrap-article">
        <div class="section-label">Phidea Weekly</div>
        <h3>Keep reading.</h3>
        <p>
          One short piece per week on AI in insurance: the regulator moves, the model updates, the things carriers are actually trying.
        </p>
        <form action="https://buttondown.email/api/emails/embed-subscribe/phidea" method="POST" class="signup">
          <input type="hidden" name="tag" value="ai-visibility" />
          <input type="email" name="email" placeholder="you@carrier.com" required />
          <button type="submit">Subscribe →</button>
        </form>
        <p class="signup-small">One email per week. Unsubscribe in one click.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>

  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .wrap-article { max-width: 680px; padding-left: 24px; padding-right: 24px; margin: 0 auto; }

  .article-head { padding: 72px 0 32px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line); }
  .article-meta {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--muted);
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
  .article-head h1 {
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 44px;
    line-height: 1.12;
    letter-spacing: -0.015em;
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .standfirst {
    font-size: 20px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    margin: 0;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .article-body { padding: 48px 0 64px; }
  .article-body p {
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.72;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-weight: 400;
  }
  .article-body p code {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background: var(--soft);
    padding: 1px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }

  .section-label {
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .subscribe-strip {
    padding: 72px 0;
    background: var(--soft);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
  }
  .subscribe-strip h3 {
    font-family: 'Fraunces', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 28px;
    line-height: 1.2;
    margin: 0 0 12px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .subscribe-strip p {
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--ink-2);
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-family: inherit;
  }
  .signup { display: flex; gap: 10px; max-width: 520px; }
  .signup input[type=email] {
    flex: 1;
    padding: 14px 16px;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 10px;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-family: inherit;
    background: var(--bg);
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .signup button {
    padding: 14px 24px;
    border: none;
    background: var(--ink);
    color: var(--bg);
    border-radius: 10px;
    font-weight: 500;
    cursor: pointer;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-family: inherit;
  }
  .signup button:hover { background: var(--accent); }
  .signup-small {
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin-top: 12px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .article-head h1 { font-size: 30px; }
    .standfirst { font-size: 17px; }
    .article-body p { font-size: 17px; }
    .signup { flex-direction: column; }
  }
</style>
